\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandrameen was ushered out of his little cave cell through the crack. the torch, whose name, Mandri had learned, was Hill.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandrameen stood up and stretched his back, all the while gawking at Oro. He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d never dreamed he\u8217\'92d see a Mazydai this close, or in this place of all places. He followed Hill and Moteah out of the cell and into the cave proper. She was holding the only torch, and it\u8217\'92s flickering light illuminated the narrow slip of rock under her feet. The rest of the ground fell into a large blue-green pool of algal water. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s walls were waxy and seemed to be frozen mid-melt. Glistening strands of hard seemed to drip from the ceiling like saliva on the roof of a lizard\u8217\'92s mouth. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They moved on into a tunnel that led up towards the surface. With each step the rock became dryer, and the going got steeper. Oro struggled along. He walked with his elbows tucked tight against his body, fearing to brush his arms against a stray shadow of a rock. It compromised his balance, and coupled with the recent loss of blood, he was sure to move slowly.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The others accomodated him. Oro cut such a tragic figure that, even though Moteah and Sandie despised him in principle, they couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t help but pity him. They weren\u8217\'92t cruel people, but this little march felt cruel.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Here and there they would pass a tunnels that spread off in odd directions, up and down, skewing this way that, leading off into some unknown abyss.}
